# Tech Stack

- Language: TypeScript.
- Platform: Visual Studio Code extension (the standard VS Code Extension API).
  The extension must also work in Cursor, which is a VS Code fork - targeting the
  standard API covers both, so do not use anything Cursor-specific.
- Scaffold with the standard tooling (yo code / generator-code) producing a normal
  package.json extension manifest with activation events and contributed commands.
- UI tiles are rendered in a VS Code Webview.
- Node.js APIs (child_process, etc.) are available in the extension host for
  shelling out to tmux and git.
- Target OS: macOS and Linux only. Do not write Windows-specific code; SwarmForge
  depends on tmux.

# Conventions

- Keep the extension-host code and the webview code clearly separated. They are
  different execution contexts that communicate only by message passing
  (postMessage). Do not attempt to share state directly between them.
- The extension host owns all I/O: shelling to tmux, reading .swarmforge/ files,
  running git. The webview is purely presentation plus user input forwarded back
  to the host.
- Prefer small, testable modules. The cleaner agent will improve coverage and
  structure, so write code that is easy to refactor.
- Use clear command IDs namespaced under "swarmforge." (e.g. swarmforge.run,
  swarmforge.stop, swarmforge.setTarget, swarmforge.initTarget).

# Design and testability

- Work in small, reviewable increments.
- Prefer the simplest design that supports the current behavior and leaves clear
  options for the next step.
- Keep tests close to the behavior being changed.
- Separate testable modules (pure TypeScript logic) from environmentally
  unsuitable modules — code that needs the live VS Code API, a webview DOM, a
  real tmux server, or the network. Maximize the testable core and keep the
  unsuitable boundary thin (small adapters over vscode.*, child_process, tmux).
- Only testable modules participate in tools that run tests: unit tests,
  acceptance tests, coverage, mutation, CRAP, and DRY analysis that invokes
  tests. Never point those tools at boundary modules that would open UI, spawn
  tmux, or hang under automation.

# Hardening tools (run from extension/, separate from `npm test`)

- Mutation testing (Stryker): `npm run mutation` compiles, then mutates the
  built output under out/ and runs the unit suite against each mutant,
  reporting killed vs surviving mutants. A whole-codebase run is SLOW (the
  full suite runs per mutant); the intended mode is differential, on the
  files you changed: `npm run mutation -- --mutate "out/<path>.js"`. The run
  maintains `stryker-incremental.json` (committed; do not delete or gitignore
  it) so later runs only re-test what changed. Mutants in TypeScript's emitted
  module boilerplate (e.g. __createBinding) are noise — target survivors in
  code you own.
- DRY duplication (jscpd): `npm run dry` scans extension/src and reports
  duplicated blocks with counts and percentages.
- CRAP metric (custom, no turnkey JS CLI exists): `npm run crap` regenerates
  coverage (`npm run coverage`, c8 JSON reporter mapped back to TS source via
  source maps) then reports each function's cyclomatic complexity, coverage
  fraction, and CRAP = comp^2 * (1-cov)^3 + comp, flagging any function over
  6 and exiting non-zero when it finds one. Differential mode takes explicit
  files, mirroring Stryker's own `--mutate` pattern:
  `node scripts/crapReport.js src/panel/badgeSummary.ts`. Keep CRAP at or
  below 6 on changed code (hardender.prompt).
- None of these tools are part of `npm test`; they are hardener/developer
  commands.

# Acceptance pipeline (Gherkin)

- Use github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification (APS) for Gherkin
  acceptance tests.
- The specifier's Gherkin scenarios in each backlog item's `acceptance:` field
  are where scenarios are born; the acceptance pipeline is what turns them into
  executable acceptance tests. Accepted scenarios accumulate as feature files
  under test/acceptance/ and become the permanent regression acceptance suite.
- APS supplies `gherkin-parser` and `gherkin-mutator`; install or build those
  commands from that repository instead of reimplementing them in this repo.
  Resolve the repo at its latest upstream version; do not rely on stale cached
  copies when a fresh install is possible.
- Prefer the Babashka APS tools (bb is already a SwarmForge dependency, so it is
  on PATH). Use the Go-based APS tools only if the Babashka ones do not work in
  the current environment.
- The project-specific pipeline components live in this repo, in TypeScript:
  the acceptance entrypoint generator, acceptance runtime, project step
  handlers, runner adapter, and convenience scripts (e.g. `npm run acceptance`,
  `npm run acceptance:mutate`). Step handlers drive the testable modules only —
  never a live VS Code window or a real tmux server.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation means running `gherkin-mutator` to mutate the
  Gherkin example values (not the source code) and confirming the acceptance
  tests fail on the mutated examples — proof the examples are actually wired to
  behavior rather than decorative.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation runs must report periodic progress/status so
  agents can distinguish normal long-running work from a hang.
- Acceptance tools are not part of `npm test`. QA owns running the acceptance
  gate; building and fixing the pipeline components themselves is regular
  development work scheduled through the backlog like any other item.

# Verification

- Before running build or test commands, prefer project-local cache and
  configuration paths inside your assigned worktree (npm cache, c8/Stryker temp
  dirs) over default locations that write outside the project and can trip
  sandbox or permission restrictions.
- Run acceptance generation and acceptance tests sequentially; avoid running
  the whole unit suite concurrently with acceptance generation.

# Guardrails

- Do not edit tool-maintained manifests by hand (`stryker-incremental.json`,
  any Gherkin acceptance mutation manifest); let the approved tools update them
  as part of their normal runs.
- Do not commit unrelated local changes. Generated output this repo
  deliberately tracks (out/, `stryker-incremental.json`) is committed with the
  change that regenerates it; do not add new kinds of generated artifacts
  unless the task requires it.
- Before relying on an unfamiliar command, inspect its local help or the
  project documentation.

# Architecture rules (important - these prevent the project going off the rails)

1. Two layers: tile-as-view, tmux-as-substrate.
   - The tiles are TypeScript/webview VIEWS. tmux is the process SUBSTRATE that
     actually runs the agents (SwarmForge's model).
   - These are NOT alternatives - they are different layers. The tile renders and
     forwards input; tmux runs the agents underneath.
   - DO NOT spawn agent processes directly from TypeScript to avoid tmux. That
     would mean reimplementing SwarmForge's orchestration and is explicitly wrong.
     If a task starts to feel like rebuilding process orchestration, stop - that is
     the signal you have crossed this line.

2. Integrate, do not fork.
   - SwarmForge is a pinned, unmodified, separately-installed dependency. Do not
     copy its source into this repo. Interact with it only through:
       - launching its ./swarm wrapper,
       - reading its state under .swarmforge/ (including .swarmforge/tmux-socket),
       - attaching to its tmux sessions/panes,
       - reading its swarmforge.conf to learn the role/window topology.

3. Webview storage restriction.
   - Do NOT use localStorage, sessionStorage, or any browser storage in the webview.
     Keep UI state in memory or persist via the extension host (VS Code workspace
     state / files). Browser storage is not reliable in this context.

4. Secrets.
   - Any tokens or keys (e.g. a GitHub token for opening PRs) live in the extension
     host environment only. Never write them into the target's working directory or
     into any commit.

# Key integration surface to get working first

Before building UI polish, prove these against a real SwarmForge install, in this
order (this is the riskiest part):

1. Launch a swarm against a target path by shelling to ./swarm.
2. Discover SwarmForge's tmux socket (.swarmforge/tmux-socket) and enumerate its
   sessions/windows/panes.
3. Tail one pane's output into a webview tile, live.
4. Send keystrokes INTO a pane (needed for interactive tiles) - this is the
   fiddliest cross-platform piece, so tackle it early.
5. Read .swarmforge/ state to know which stage holds the work.
6. Open a PR from the dev branch into the target's main using git + the GitHub CLI
   or API.

If any of these cannot be done by driving SwarmForge from outside, note it clearly
rather than working around it by modifying SwarmForge - it may be something to
request upstream.
